 ('82', '105', '1', '1', 'en_us', '1', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Northern California, Oregon, and Portland\",\"slug\":\"northern-california-oregon-and-portland\",\"postDate\":1377278700,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>\\r\\n\\t  Two months!  I have not posted in two months! Not since Tuolumne Meadows! And now I am sitting at my friend Dave\'s house in Portland, where I will be leading a backpacking trip for Reed College starting tomorrow morning.  Yes, that\'s right, I got off the Pacific Crest Trail to lead a backpacking trip.  Everyone seems to find that mildly amusing.  The timing just worked out so perfectly and I enjoy leading Reedies into the wilderness so much that it was awfully hard to say no.  Also, the money I will make by leading nine freshmen and two upperclassmen student leaders into the Mt. Adams Wilderness will pay for all of Washington.  Nice!\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\\t  So, the last two months were intense and long. Goodall and I made it through the Sierras tired but mostly intact.  Her parents met us again at Sonora Pass and gave us a tasty dinner and took the unwieldy bear canisters away.  Then, we entered what must have been the birthplace of the first mosquitos, as they were there in force.  Entire flocks followed us for days.  Headnets and DEET not optional.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\\t Finally, we entered Northern California where we enjoyed many days of temperatures near 100 degrees Fahrenheit and plenty of volcanic rocks through old burn areas.  It had more than its fair share of unpleasant days. Upon finishing the 30+ dry stretch that is Hat Creek Rim, I remember looking at two fellow hikers, Lotus and Hermes, and we all just looked completely spent. Shortly after, near Burney Falls, I got my worst blister yet.  The intense heat caused a large blister to form <em>underneath<\\/em> the callous on the ball of my left foot.  Was hardly able to walk for two days.  And then my iPhone got stolen while at Castella, which had me psychologically break down for an hour (maps, notes, music, photos, videos...buh-bye) and then head into Mt. Shasta, where I charmed my way into getting a brand new phone that afternoon and at a reduced cost.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\\t There were really good days too.  In Sierra City, nearly everyone took at least one zero and I got to catch up with many old hiking friends.  In Seiad City, Goodall and I spent the night with two Reed alums who lived just down the road; enjoying a quiet night with showers, laundry, home cooked meal, and beds.  And let\'s not forget that sunset near Mt. Shasta where the sky came alive with layers of clouds and color.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\\t Near the Oregon border, we had our first taste of forest fires and their smoke.  A lightning storm a few days prior had started at least four fires in Oregon and their smoke drifted down into California.  At one point we were doing a long climb and you could hardly see the hillside across from you.  Blowing our noses at every break to clear out the particulate matter too.   Ashland and Medford had such bad smoke that the outdoor plays were canceled.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\\t Near Crater Lake, I got my first taste of Oregon weather madness.  Not sure what it is, but whenever I am on the Pacific Crest Trail during August in Oregon, I always seem to have forest fires and rain.  Naturally, I had not checked the weather before leaving Ashland and had forwarded my rain pants on.  Thankfully I kept my Smartwool beanie as there were quite a few chilly nights.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\\t Right around the Three Sisters Wilderness, Oregon became absolutely gorgeous.  Cookie and I dry camped shortly before Obsidian Creek and enjoyed a lovely sunset and sunrise to the west of Middle Sister. Sadly, the next day had us hiking through at least five miles total of volcanic rock near McKenzie Pass followed by a long burn area.  I am ever so glad I changed my plans and took a night off in Sisters.  Gave me a chance to catch up with a former coworker, eat good food, and just relax before the final push to Timberline Lodge.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"3\":\"pct\"}}', '2013-08-23 17:25:38', '2015-01-17 19:43:04', '198b32dc-3931-44d0-8790-bc83b4ffeb1a'),
