 ('204', '130', '1', '1', 'en_us', '9', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"The Secret Life of the Thru-Hiker\",\"slug\":\"the-secret-life-of-the-thru-hiker\",\"postDate\":1384032600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Returning to civilization has been more of a struggle than I expected.  While thru-hiking, I can only remember a few mornings when it was truly difficult to get out of my sleeping bag and continue hiking. Most days that simple, focused purpose of continuing North was enough motivation.  That drive forward is so powerful that injuries that should be given a week off rarely get a single day.<\\/p><p>Back here in the Real World, it all feels so ridiculously complicated.  There are so many considerations that need to be carefully origami\'ed into my life: employment, money, living situation, bills, driving, socializing, rehabilitation of injured parts, and even what to eat. Over six weeks of being off trail and I am still experiencing a low level of anxiety every single day.  It is not a pleasant experience.<\\/p><p>Not exactly fantasizing about being back on the trail either. That trip is over. But, I am definitely thinking about the <em>next<\\/em> trip; the next time that I can get be <em>out <strong>there<\\/strong><\\/em>. For me, \\\"Why am I here?\\\" is a constant refrain in my mind.  Why should I not be out there in the forests, deserts, and mountains of the world? Isn\'t that where I belong?  Staring out a coffee shop window at the gorgeous autumn weather when I should be examining spreadsheets for the new job is definitely reinforcing this feeling.<\\/p><p>Still, I must bend my will to spending time here and refilling the coffers and reconnecting with people, relearning to labor and wait.  Just for a while longer.<\\/p>\",\"3\":\"personal\"}}', '2013-11-10 18:42:26', '2015-01-17 19:43:04', '8d260200-87c1-4559-911b-d3f7c3041920'),
 ('205', '130', '1', '1', 'en_us', '10', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"The Secret Life of the Thru-Hiker\",\"slug\":\"the-secret-life-of-the-thru-hiker\",\"postDate\":1384032600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Returning to civilization has been more of a struggle than I expected.  While thru-hiking I can only remember a few mornings when it was exceptionally difficult to get out of my sleeping bag and continue hiking. Most days that simple, focused, and uncompromising purpose of continuing <strong><em>North<\\/em><\\/strong> was sufficient motivation.  That drive forward on the trail is so powerful that even serious injuries that should have been given a week off rarely got more than a single day.  When I took two full days off, it was obvious to every single thru-hiker that I was in serious pain.<\\/p><p>Back here in the Real World, it all feels so ridiculously complicated.  There are so many considerations that need to be carefully Tetris\'ed into my life: employment, money, living situation, bills, driving, socializing, rehabilitation of injured parts, and even what to eat. Over six weeks of being off trail and I am still experiencing a low level of anxiety every single day.  It is not a pleasant experience.  So bad that most times when I visit the grocery store, I only grab fresh produce and chocolate.  Circulating among the other aisles stresses me out.<\\/p><p>Not exactly fantasizing about being back on the trail either. That trip is over. But, I am definitely thinking about the <em>next<\\/em> trip; the next time that I can get be <em>out <strong>there<\\/strong><\\/em>. For me, \\\"Why am I here?\\\" is a constant refrain in my mind.  Why should I not be out there in the forests, deserts, and mountains of the world? Isn\'t that where I belong?  Staring out a coffee shop window at the gorgeous autumn weather when I should be examining spreadsheets for the new job is definitely reinforcing this feeling.<\\/p><p>Still, I must bend my will to spending time <em>here;<\\/em> refilling the coffers and reconnecting with people, relearning to labor and wait.  Just for a while longer.<\\/p>\",\"3\":\"personal\"}}', '2013-11-24 18:23:17', '2015-01-17 19:43:04', 'be624fc4-bfb6-4cc3-8df6-a7d38e3178b0'),
 ('206', '131', '1', '1', 'en_us', '1', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Negative, Ghost Rider, The Mind is Full\",\"slug\":\"negative-ghost-rider-the-mind-is-full\",\"postDate\":1385325638,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>The disconnection from self and life stemming from my thru-hike is rather difficult to verbalize.  Ask me details about how to pull of backpacking 2600+ miles and I can talk your ear off.  Ask me how I am handling being back and how the experience changed me, and in no uncertain terms I fail for the right words.  Hours and hours have been wasted trying to write it down with it never becoming sufficiently coherent or organized for posting.<\\/p><p>Thankfully, I have Amelia both as my best friend and a fellow thru-hiker.  She <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/ameliorator.blogspot.com\\/2013\\/11\\/recalibrating.html\\\">captured perfectly<\\/a> my feelings and difficulties in reintegrating to society.  Many a time I have wanted to simply hire her as a ghostwriter.<\\/p><p>Friends have asked me if I am depressed. I cannot say for sure, but I do not <em>feel<\\/em> like I am suffering from depression.  Getting up every morning, going to work and contributing, eating healthy, daily exercise, sleeping reasonably well, and the next six months of my life are slowly being planned out.  Instead of a lack of energy, I feel an overwhelming surplus of it.  And time, so much time.  How do you people handle weekends? And nights?  Been hanging around a few new people since I have been back, and it seems the general approach is TV and drinking.  Seriously, this is how I am supposed to spend my time?  I do not mind small doses...but definitely not as a hobby.<\\/p><p>The denial is the oddest part of the whole shebang.  I can understand the disconnection, listlessness, and feeling that I am a stranger in my own life.  But, my mind is having a hard time accepting that the trail happened.  I have vivid memories of the highs, the lows, the pains, the joys; they come back every time I stare out a coffee shop window or log into Facebook to see fellow thru-hikers\' photos.  And yet, I cannot accept it.  Feels like an odd dream.  A little fantastical concoction my mind imagined up.  Or else, any morning I am going to wake up back in my tent having only just gotten to the Oregon border.<\\/p>\",\"3\":\"pct\"}}', '2013-11-24 20:40:38', '2015-01-17 19:43:04', '05450105-70e9-48dc-a67d-d6ed91fc9966'),
