 ('208', '131', '1', '1', 'en_us', '3', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Negative, Ghost Rider, The Mind is Full\",\"slug\":\"negative-ghost-rider-the-mind-is-full\",\"postDate\":1385325600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>The disconnection from self and life stemming from my thru-hike is rather difficult to verbalize.  Ask me details about how to successfully backpack 2600+ miles and I can talk your ear off.  Ask me how I am handling being back and how the experience changed me, and I fail for the right words.  Hours and hours have been wasted trying to write it down with it never becoming sufficiently coherent or organized for posting.<\\/p><p>Thankfully, I have Amelia both as my best friend and a fellow thru-hiker.  She <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/ameliorator.blogspot.com\\/2013\\/11\\/recalibrating.html\\\">captured perfectly<\\/a> my feelings and difficulties in reintegrating to society.  Many a time I have wanted to simply hire her as a ghostwriter.<\\/p><p>Friends have asked me if I am depressed. I cannot say for sure, but I do not <em>feel<\\/em> like I am suffering from depression.  Getting up every morning, going to work and contributing, eating healthy, daily exercise, sleeping reasonably well, and the next six months of my life are slowly being planned out.  Instead of a lack of energy, I feel an overwhelming surplus of it.  And time, so much time.  How do you people handle weekends? And nights?  Been hanging around new people since I have been back, and it seems the general approach is TV and drinking.  Seriously, this is how I am supposed to spend my time?  I do not mind small doses but definitely not as a hobby.<\\/p><p>The denial is the oddest part of the whole shebang.  I can understand the disconnection, listlessness, and feeling that I am a stranger in my own life.  But, my mind is having a hard time accepting that the trail happened.  I have vivid memories of the highs, the lows, the pains, the joys; they come back every time I stare out a coffee shop window or log into Facebook to see fellow thru-hikers\' photos.  And yet, I cannot accept it.  Feels like an odd dream.  A little fantastical concoction my mind imagined up.<\\/p><p>When people exclaim how amazing I am for finishing, I just nod.  It does not feel amazing.  It does not feel complete. There is something missing.  That proverbial other shoe has not dropped. I do not feel like I finished the trail, I feel like I need to go back and finish it.  I am not amazing or complete yet.   There is more yet to do!<\\/p><p>Amelia brings up the idea of \\\"dosing\\\" ourselves with these adventures.  And that is EXACTLY right.  Fun Size, Cuddles, Hermes and Lotus, G-Bird, Goodall, and myself are all on Facebook planting the seeds for our next trips.  Appalachian Trail? Continental Divide Trail? Antarctica? Himalayan Pass Tour?  Just get us back there.  We <em>need<\\/em> to go back.<\\/p>\",\"3\":\"pct\"}}', '2013-11-24 20:53:48', '2015-01-17 19:43:04', 'a47221e2-14cb-4bbe-a5d5-73c1248f2d9b'),
