t of weight behind it. At its core, it is a catchall term meaning one is trying to make the world better though some manner of giving, be it money, property, or personal time. Like any product, we are trying to solve a problem. If you are truly serious about having an impact with your giving, it is currently a messy and inefficient process. Each non-profit has its own website and their projects may or may not be on it. How their projects impact the community may not be readily apparent. Directly investing in a specific project that catches your eye may not be possible. An individual or company can literally spend months searching for the perfect place to give their money, yet still end up just writing a check to the non-profit as a general donation.<\\/p><p>On the flip side, non-profits are always searching for funds and donors. Significant amounts of their budgets are spent finding and applying for grants, contacting donors, and building corporate relationships to insure their projects are funded. Smaller, community-focused non-profits often lose out to more publicly recognizable non-profits. And, if they want to promote how their current projects are doing, they are limited by the capabilities of their website and social media team, if they even have one.<\\/p><p>Imagine if you could bring both sides, funders and non-profits, to one place and meet all of those needs. Funders can build their own giving funds and indicate where they want the money to go. Interested in giving $5,000 twice a year to Child Development projects in Seattle run by validated non-profits? ImpactFlow will help you. Non-Profts with projects on the site that meet your requirements will be notified of your fund and can submit their project for your review. You evaluate the applicants and grant the money to those you and your team deem the best. Once a project is funded by you, the Non-Profit can post updates and impact stories, which you will be automatically notified of.<\\/p><p>There is quite a bit more to the platform, but that is the seed at the core of it. We want to move beyond giving as it currently stands and allow it to be treated more as a professional investment.<\\/p><p>---<\\/p><p>When I joined the company as a developer at the end of November, I was only the fourth employee and was primarily hired because of my knowledge and experience with the&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/ellislab.com\\/codeigniter\\\">CodeIgniter<\\/a> framework, which I helped build during my time at EllisLab. Last week I was promoted to VP of Engineering and have built a rather significant API foundation for the entire platform using&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/laravel.com\\\">Laravel<\\/a>. &nbsp;The scope of the platform, even at this initial launch phase, is simply mind bending. And our list of future enhancements and features is ambitious to say the least. &nbsp;<\\/p><p>To be frank, I took this job because my savings were so depleted after finishing the Pacific Crest Trail that any potential development position with enough challenge to keep me motivated would have done. Now, after helping to design and build not only the platform but the company itself, I have both an equity and personal investment in its success.<\\/p><p>The scars of 2012 still haunt me every day. &nbsp;As much as part of me craves to continue my pursuit of medicine and attempt to make the world better that way, I cannot will myself to plunge into that level of financial debt any longer. I lost too much faith and became too greedy for a life without that level of sacrifice.<\\/p><p>What I can do is use all of my technical skills to build a company whose mission statement is explicit in its goal to make things better. &nbsp;Not sure how long I will resist the call of extreme outdoor adventures, but I do not mind terribly accepting a bit of responsibility in the meantime.&nbsp;<\\/p>\",\"3\":\"technology\"}}', '2014-05-22 04:35:47', '2015-01-17 19:43:04', '6c0ae6a7-0475-43bc-86fc-314bde5df7fd'),
