while also helping to eliminate those whose characteristics you believe would not bode well for a relationship with you. And yet, wow, can you not rely on their algorithms at all when it comes to in-person chemistry. Five minutes in person is worth more than days or weeks talking online. And then there is the feeling of being on a marketplace and being forced to prioritize who you interact with first in order to prevent messy complications. The site developers have made the entire process fascinating and addictive, but in the end it seems woefully inadequate and problematic.<\\/p><p>In-person interactions are far more rewarding, at least initially. Eye contact, flirting, and casual conversational chemistry are great fun. Ah, but then you hit the roadblocks. Oh, not single (x5). Oh, not actually from Portland. Oh, does drugs. Oh, she\'s 22. Oh, she\'s moving in two months to the other side of the country. My forehead is developing a callous from all the facepalms. To continue the science metaphor, it is like receiving amazing initial results and then finding out it was all a computer glitch. It is quite maddening. You start getting tired of going into the lab at all.<\\/p><p>And that is just the first step. That, my friends, is just trying to get the coveted First Date.<\\/p><p>Maybe it is a combination of my unyielding inner child and slight bias against typical American adulthood, but when did people get so serious about their immediate futures? Without an ounce of exaggeration or sarcasm, I tell you I have been on a first date where I would have been greatly served by bringing a full DNA and psychological profile so my paternal potential could be efficiently evaluated. Never have I felt so viewed less as a person and more as a sperm donor. &nbsp;Why have a conversation to determine if you even like me as a person before evaluating the potential of our future offspring?<\\/p><p>And, good lord, would I not mind talking about my thru-hike and my desire for additional adventures without the question of my continued residence in the Portland area being brought up. My long term plans are unknown and I offer no&nbsp;guarantees on a first, second, or third date that I will absolutely be around in three months. It is even more ludicrous than employers not wanting to hire me when I admit I <em>might<\\/em> want to move on in a year.&nbsp;I have been informed this has been interpreted as a fear of commitment, fear of being hurt, or a wish to play the field. A friend has even gone so far as to tell me I should lie more often about what is going on in my head. Something about me thinking too much and by sharing all the thoughts flying through my head I scare women...or something like that, I got distracted midway through the conversation. In the end, I refuse to be dishonest or misleading. While it may serve me poorly in the dating realm, it keeps my brain from throwing a synaptic tantrum.<\\/p><p>All in all, the entire process is ridiculously unrelaxing. At this point I am befuddled as to how I was ever in a relationship before.<\\/p>\",\"3\":\"personal\"}}', '2014-10-13 03:03:37', '2015-01-17 19:43:04', 'a82180b2-cc73-4d72-b5bf-f7468bfc194f'),
