 ('343', '162', '1', '1', 'en_us', '3', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"The Relationship with Work\",\"slug\":\"the-relationship-with-work\",\"postDate\":1427771820,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Not sure whether it is the season (<em>In the Spring a young man\'s fancy lightly turns to<\\/em><em>...<\\/em>job hunting?) but there seems to be no shortage of people currently seeking a change in employment.  Numerous thru-hikers on Facebook are on their way to, or seriously contemplating, their next hike or adventure. Three friends in technology have expressed frustration with their current work and have started polishing their resume for entrance into the market.  And a certain redheaded baker up North is on the phone with me about once a week wondering how long she will last.<span><\\/span><\\/p><p><br><\\/p>\",\"3\":\"personal\"}}', '2015-03-31 03:22:46', '2015-03-31 03:22:46', '5d2f7d73-a6a9-4552-abd6-3359aa7b7902'),
 ('344', '162', '1', '1', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"The Relationship with Work\",\"slug\":\"the-relationship-with-work\",\"postDate\":1427771820,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Not sure whether it is the season (<em>In the Spring a young man\'s fancy lightly turns to<\\/em><em>...<\\/em>job hunting?) but there seems to be no shortage of people currently seeking a change in employment.  Numerous thru-hikers on Facebook are on their way to, or seriously contemplating, their next hike or adventure. Three friends in technology have expressed frustration with their current work and have started polishing their resume for entrance into the market.  And a certain redheaded baker up North is on the phone with me about once a week wondering how long she will last.<\\/p><p>I myself probably consider my employment at least once a day.  I am a contemplative sort so that should not be overly surprising. While talking to one of those potential seekers today, I wondered if one can rightly compare employment to a relationship.  Here you spend 40+ hours a week in the company of your job.  People move across states, countries, and continents for their job. It provides some manner of fulfillment via monetary, emotional, or egotistical means.<\\/p><p>If you were to say to me that you are in a romantic relationship that is merely \\\"ok\\\" or \\\"is not that great\\\", my advice would be to leave and find a new one. Your time and life are valuable.  Why spend it <\\/p>\",\"3\":\"personal\"}}', '2015-03-31 03:32:09', '2015-03-31 03:32:09', '5fcc5c9e-0c98-4101-af44-ba52cfeb1d69'),
 ('345', '162', '1', '1', 'en_us', '5', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"The Relationship with Work\",\"slug\":\"the-relationship-with-work\",\"postDate\":1427771820,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>\\r\\n\\tNot sure whether it is the season (<em>In the Spring a young man\'s fancy lightly turns to<\\/em><em>...<\\/em>job hunting?) but there seems to be no shortage of people currently seeking a change in employment.  Numerous thru-hikers on Facebook are on their way to, or seriously contemplating, their next hike or adventure. Three friends in technology have expressed frustration with their current work and have started polishing their resume for entrance into the market.  And a certain redheaded baker up North is on the phone with me once a week wondering how long she will last. I myself probably consider my employment at least once a day.  I am a contemplative sort so that should not be overly surprising.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\tWhile talking to one of those potential seekers today, I wondered if one can rightly compare employment to a relationship.  Here you spend 40+ hours a week in the company of your job.  People move across states, countries, and continents for their work. It provides some manner of fulfillment via monetary, emotional, or egotistical means. And it greatly influences nearly every major decision you will make.<br>\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\tNow, if you were to say to me that you are in a romantic relationship that is merely \\\"ok\\\" or \\\"not that great\\\", my advice would be to leave and find a new one. Your time and life are valuable.  Why spend a fourth of your life in a situation that you could potentially change for the better?\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\tYes, yes, we do not live in a post-scarcity utopia where are ability to flutter between jobs is without restraint.  But, you do have quite a bit of power here.  One of my favorite quotes in this area comes from the late Steve Jobs:\\r\\n<\\/p><blockquote>I have looked in the mirror every morning and asked myself: \\\"If today were the last day of my life, would I want to do what I am about to do today?\\\" And whenever the answer has been \\\"No\\\" for too many days in a row, I know I need to change something.<br><\\/blockquote><p>That is phenomenally good advice.  <\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\t<br>\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\t<br>\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"3\":\"personal\"}}', '2015-03-31 03:37:05', '2015-03-31 03:37:05', '8f39b384-8787-4310-9848-99e49a3d68e1'),
 ('346', '162', '1', '1', 'en_us', '6', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"The Relationship with Work\",\"slug\":\"the-relationship-with-work\",\"postDate\":1427771820,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>\\r\\n\\tNot sure whether it is the season (<em>In the Spring a young man\'s fancy lightly turns to<\\/em><em>...<\\/em>job hunting?) but there seems to be no shortage of people currently seeking a change in employment.  Numerous thru-hikers on Facebook are on their way to, or seriously contemplating, their next hike or adventure. Three friends in technology have expressed frustration with their current work and have started polishing their resume for entrance into the market.  And a certain redheaded baker up North is on the phone with me once a week wondering how long she will last. I myself probably consider my employment at least once a day.  I am a contemplative sort so that should not be overly surprising.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\tWhile talking to one of those potential seekers today, I wondered if one can rightly compare employment to a relationship.  Here you spend 40+ hours a week in the company of your job.  People move across states, countries, and continents for their work. It provides some manner of fulfillment via monetary, emotional, or egotistical means. And it greatly influences nearly every major decision you will make.<br>\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\tNow, if you were to say to me that you are in a romantic relationship that is merely \\\"ok\\\" or \\\"not that great\\\" or \\\"stresses me out\\\", my advice would be to leave and find a new one. Your time and life are valuable\\u2013nay, precious.  Why spend a fourth of your life in a situation that you could potentially change for the better?\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\tYes, yes, we do not live in a post-scarcity utopia where are ability to flutter between jobs is without restraint.  But, most of us have quite a bit of power and opportunity here, if we choose to use it.  One of my favorite quotes in this area comes from the late Steve Jobs:\\r\\n<\\/p><blockquote>I have looked in the mirror every morning and asked myself: \\\"If today were the last day of my life, would I want to do what I am about to do today?\\\" And whenever the answer has been \\\"No\\\" for too many days in a row, I know I need to change something.<\\/blockquote><p>That is phenomenally good advice.  <\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\t<br>\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\t<br>\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"3\":\"personal\"}}', '2015-03-31 03:42:19', '2015-03-31 03:42:19', 'e69b0e20-62b9-4de2-a879-04cc8794d887'),
