 ('425', '185', '1', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"September Check-In\",\"slug\":\"september-check-in\",\"postDate\":1442779200,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">So, I went to <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/sets\\/72157657725794351\\\">SE Alaska<\\/a> for two weeks and it was <em>amazing!<\\/em> Took the Alaska Marine Highway up to Ketchikan and saw gorgeous scenic beauty with multiple sightings of whales\\u2013or at least their spouts and a bit of sun glinting off their backs.  Camping on the deck worked reasonably well for the first night but then the continuous dampness and wind loosened the duct tape a bit too much and nearly everyone moved inside the solariums. Saved us from hearing the ship\'s fog horn early in the mornings too.<\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">Ketchikan lived up to its reputation of the First City (that cruise lines stop at) and being one of the rainiest cities in America. Did all the general touristy things from visiting the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/alaskacenters.gov\\/ketchikan.cfm\\\">Southeast Alaska Discovery Center<\\/a> to watching the salmon spawn up near Creek Street to seeing Totem Bite State Park.  Went for a VERY wet hike up Deer Mountain and visited its shelter where I spent a solid 15 minutes wringing out clothes and replacing calories. <br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">Discovered that Wrangell is one of the least talked about gems of the Inside Passage. Few tourists but contained my two favorite excursions, the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.wrangell.com\\/visitorservices\\/anan-bear-and-wildlife-observatory\\\">Anan Bear Observatory<\\/a> and <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20239836853\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">LeConte Glacier<\\/a>.  Both were run by <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.alaskawaters.com\\\">Alaska Waters<\\/a>, which I cannot recommend highly enough for their friendliness and good humor in accommodating a traveler who showed up with no plans, only hopes.  And, let\'s not forget my little hike up to the top of Mt. Dewey, where John Muir had has infamous fire that scared both the natives and townsfolk of Wrangell back in 1869.  It was his book that led me to take this SE Alaska sojourn in the first place, after all.<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\"><br><\\/p>\"}}', '2015-09-20 17:18:35', '2015-09-20 17:18:35', '635f990d-77e9-4169-92de-262470f8f8fa'),
