Waters<\\/a>, which I cannot recommend highly enough for their friendliness and good humor in accommodating a traveler who showed up with no plans, only hopes.  And, let\'s not forget my little hike up to the top of Mt. Dewey, where John Muir had has infamous fire that scared both the natives and townsfolk of Wrangell back in 1869.  It was his book that led me to take this SE Alaska sojourn in the first place, after all.<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\"><br><\\/p>\"}}', '2015-09-20 17:19:04', '2015-09-20 17:19:04', '1af57be8-9541-4810-a87f-f98238e6e215'),
 ('427', '185', '1', '1', 'en_us', '3', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"SE Alaska Trip Report, Better Late than Never.\",\"slug\":\"se-alaska-trip-report\",\"postDate\":1442779200,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">So, I went to <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/sets\\/72157657725794351\\\">SE Alaska<\\/a> for two weeks and it was <em>amazing!<\\/em> Took the Alaska Marine Highway up to Ketchikan and saw gorgeous scenic beauty with multiple sightings of whales\\u2013or at least their spouts and a bit of sun glinting off their backs.  Camping on the deck worked reasonably well for the first night but then the continuous dampness and wind loosened the duct tape a bit too much and nearly everyone moved inside the solariums. Saved us from hearing the ship\'s fog horn early in the mornings too.<\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">Ketchikan lived up to its reputation of the First City (that cruise lines stop at) and being one of the rainiest cities in America. Did all the general touristy things from visiting the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/alaskacenters.gov\\/ketchikan.cfm\\\">Southeast Alaska Discovery Center<\\/a> to watching the salmon spawn up near Creek Street to seeing Totem Bite State Park.  Went for a VERY wet hike up Deer Mountain and visited its wondrously well-maintained shelter where I spent a solid 15 minutes wringing out clothes and replacing calories. <br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">Discovered that Wrangell is one of the least talked about gems of the Inside Passage. Extremely few tourists but my visit there contained my two favorite excursions, the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.wrangell.com\\/visitorservices\\/anan-bear-and-wildlife-observatory\\\">Anan Bear Observatory<\\/a> and <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20239836853\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">LeConte Glacier<\\/a>.  Both were run by <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.alaskawaters.com\\\">Alaska Waters<\\/a>, which I cannot recommend highly enough for their friendliness and good humor in accommodating a traveler who showed up with no plans, only hopes.  And, let\'s not forget my little hike up to the top of Mt. Dewey, where John Muir had his infamous fire that scared both the natives and townsfolk of Wrangell back in 1869.  It was his book that led me to take this SE Alaska sojourn in the first place, after all.<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">The weather report indicated that in two days a lengthy bit of rainy weather was scheduled to hit SE Alaska, so instead of waiting a day for the ferry and then spending a day on it getting to Juneau, I took a flight to Juneau from Wrangell. It stopped in Petersburg, which was only about 12 minutes away by plane.  Up...and then down.  Then another 50 minutes or so to Juneau.  Along the way the view on the right side of the plane was the Juneau Icefield and it was <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20240059573\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">jaw dropping<\\/a>. Thanks to a conversation on the plane, I shared a cab into downtown with a pilot for one of the cruise lines.  Since the hostel did not open its doors until 5pm, I took the Mount Roberts Tramway 1,800 feet up to the Mountain House and did a quick 45 minute hike up for a better view of Juneau and the all-too-rare sunny day.<\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">The <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.juneauhostel.net\\\">Juneau Hostel<\\/a> is a bit of a wonder. Only $12 a night + one chore. There is a five night limit though, otherwise it would likely be overloaded by people staying the entire season.<\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">My next stop in Juneau was a trip to <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20673007240\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/lightbox\\/\\\">Mendenhall Glacier<\\/a> the next morning.  I foolishly grabbed one of the tourist buses there for $10 as I did not realize it only went to the Visitor Center and the Mendenhall Lake Campground was on the other side of the lake, over an hour\'s walk away.  While walking a cab came near and I hailed it down.  For $12, I skipped a 90 minute walk and was dropped off right at the West Glacier Trail trailhead.  The hike up was relatively easy and at 3.4 miles in a quick scramble brought you to a nice overlook where I got a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20673078958\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">few beautiful panoramas<\\/a>.  Hiking back down, I took an unmaintained trail and went down to the foot of the glacier to view the moraine and peek into a few ice caves. <\\/p>\"}}', '2015-09-20 17:38:34', '2015-09-20 17:38:34', 'f27c9466-8598-4436-9952-82460c50344d'),
 ('428', '185', '1', '1', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"SE Alaska Trip Report, Better Late than Never.\",\"slug\":\"se-alaska-trip-report\",\"postDate\":1442779200,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">So, I went to <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/sets\\/72157657725794351\\\">SE Alaska<\\/a> for two weeks and it was <em>amazing!<\\/em> Took the Alaska Marine Highway up to Ketchikan and saw gorgeous scenic beauty with multiple sightings of whales\\u2013or at least their spouts and a bit of sun glinting off their backs.  Camping on the deck worked reasonably well for the first night but then the continuous dampness and wind loosened the duct tape a bit too much and nearly everyone moved inside the solariums. Saved us from hearing the ship\'s fog horn early in the mornings too.<\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">Ketchikan lived up to its reputation of the First City (that cruise lines stop at) and being one of the rainiest cities in America. Did all the general touristy things from visiting the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/alaskacenters.gov\\/ketchikan.cfm\\\">Southeast Alaska Discovery Center<\\/a> to watching the salmon spawn up near Creek Street to seeing Totem Bite State Park.  Went for a VERY wet hike up Deer Mountain and visited its wondrously well-maintained shelter where I spent a solid 15 minutes wringing out clothes and replacing calories. <br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">Discovered that Wrangell is one of the least talked about gems of the Inside Passage. Extremely few tourists but my visit there contained my two favorite excursions, the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.wrangell.com\\/visitorservices\\/anan-bear-and-wildlife-observatory\\\">Anan Bear Observatory<\\/a> and <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20239836853\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">LeConte Glacier<\\/a>.  Both were run by <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.alaskawaters.com\\\">Alaska Waters<\\/a>, which I cannot recommend highly enough for their friendliness and good humor in accommodating a traveler who showed up with no plans, only hopes.  And, let\'s not forget my little hike up to the top of Mt. Dewey, where John Muir had his infamous fire that scared both the natives and townsfolk of Wrangell back in 1869.  It was his book that led me to take this SE Alaska sojourn in the first place, after all.<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">The weather report indicated that in two days a lengthy bit of rainy weather was scheduled to hit SE Alaska, so instead of waiting a day for the ferry and then spending a day on it getting to Juneau, I took a flight to Juneau from Wrangell. It stopped in Petersburg, which was only about 12 minutes away by plane.  Up...and then down.  Then another 50 minutes or so to Juneau.  Along the way the view on the right side of the plane was the Juneau Icefield and it was <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20240059573\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">jaw dropping<\\/a>. Thanks to a conversation on the plane, I shared a cab into downtown with a pilot for one of the cruise lines.  Since the hostel did not open its doors until 5pm, I took the Mount Roberts Tramway 1,800 feet up to the Mountain House and did a quick 45 minute hike up for a better view of Juneau and the all-too-rare sunny day.<\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">The <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.juneauhostel.net\\\">Juneau Hostel<\\/a> is a bit of a wonder. Only $12 a night + one chore. There is a five night limit though, otherwise it would likely be overloaded by people staying the entire season.<\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">My next stop in Juneau was a trip to <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20673007240\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/lightbox\\/\\\">Mendenhall Glacier<\\/a> the next morning.  I foolishly grabbed one of the tourist buses there for $10 as I did not realize it only went to the Visitor Center and the Mendenhall Lake Campground was on the other side of the lake, over an hour\'s walk away.  While walking a cab came near and I hailed it down.  For $12, I skipped a 90 minute walk and was dropped off right at the West Glacier Trail trailhead.  The hike up was relatively easy and at 3.4 miles in a quick scramble brought you to a nice overlook where I got a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20673078958\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">few beautiful panoramas<\\/a>.  Hiking back down, I took an unmaintained, mildly rugged offshoot trail and headed down to the foot of the glacier to view the moraine and peek into a few ice caves. The weather and glacier were superb and I felt incredibly lucky to have an entire day of clear weather to explore it. <\\/p><p style=\\\"margin-left: 40px;\\\">That evening one of the hostel guests showed me some of her photos from her whale watching tour that day. A group of humpbacks had been bubble net feeding in the area for days and it was truly a sight to see.  Unfortunately, the next morning I discovered the whale tour I had wanted to get one had been canceled because of cruise ships leaving early or changing their tour schedules. Backpackers are a very very small minority of the visitors in SE Alaska and the cruise ships really do run the show. With no other plans, I consulted my handy Lonely Planet guide and learned of the Taku Glacier and Taku Lodge seaplane tour.  Within an hour I was in a plane and flying towards Taku Glacier for a scenic tour of the nearby icefield and a king salmon dinner at the lodge.  And it just so happened that a black bear showed up to clear the drippings off of the grill.  While the tour was a bit pricey <\\/p>\"}}', '2015-09-20 17:44:54', '2015-09-20 17:44:54', '75901f8a-5b35-4cf2-a2e2-db564558058b'),
