highly enough for their friendliness and good humor in accommodating a traveler who showed up with no plans, only hopes.  And, let\'s not forget my little hike up to the top of Mt. Dewey, where John Muir had his infamous fire that scared both the natives and townsfolk of Wrangell back in 1869.  It was his book that led me to take this SE Alaska sojourn in the first place, after all.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>The weather report indicated that in two days a lengthy bit of rainy weather was scheduled to hit SE Alaska, so instead of waiting a day for the ferry and then spending a day on it getting to Juneau, I took a flight to Juneau from Wrangell. It stopped in Petersburg, which was only about 12 minutes away by plane.  Up...and then down.  Then another 50 minutes or so to Juneau.  Along the way the view on the right side of the plane was the Juneau Icefield and it was <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20240059573\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">jaw dropping<\\/a>. Thanks to a conversation on the plane, I shared a cab into downtown with a pilot for one of the cruise lines.  Since the hostel did not open its doors until 5pm, I took the Mount Roberts Tramway 1,800 feet up to the Mountain House and did a quick 45 minute hike up for a better view of Juneau and the all-too-rare sunny day.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>The <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.juneauhostel.net\\\">Juneau Hostel<\\/a> is a bit of a wonder. Only $12 a night + one chore. There is a five night limit though, otherwise it would likely be overloaded by people staying the entire season.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>My next stop in Juneau was a trip to <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20673007240\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/lightbox\\/\\\">Mendenhall Glacier<\\/a> the next morning.  I foolishly grabbed one of the tourist buses there for $10 as I did not realize it only went to the Visitor Center and the Mendenhall Lake Campground was on the other side of the lake, over an hour\'s walk away.  While walking a cab came near and I hailed it down.  For $12, I skipped a 90 minute walk and was dropped off right at the West Glacier Trail trailhead.  The hike up was relatively easy and at 3.4 miles in a quick scramble brought you to a nice overlook where I got a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20673078958\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">few beautiful panoramas<\\/a>.  Hiking back down, I took an unmaintained, mildly rugged offshoot trail and headed down to the foot of the glacier to view the moraine and peek into a few ice caves. The weather and glacier were superb and I felt incredibly lucky to have an entire day of clear weather to explore it.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>That evening one of the hostel guests showed me some of her photos from her whale watching tour that day. A group of humpbacks had been bubble net feeding in the area for days and it was truly a sight to see.  Unfortunately, the next morning I discovered the whale tour I had wanted to get one had been canceled because of cruise ships leaving early or changing their tour schedules. Backpackers are a very very small minority of the visitors in SE Alaska and the cruise ships really do run the show. With no other plans, I consulted my handy Lonely Planet guide and learned of the Taku Glacier and Taku Lodge seaplane tour.  Within an hour I was in a plane and flying towards Taku Glacier for a scenic tour of the nearby icefield and a king salmon dinner at the lodge.  And it just so happened that a black bear showed up to clear the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20673100940\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">drippings off of the grill<\\/a>.  While the tour was definitely a bit pricey, I have never had such amazing views of a glacier <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20240159833\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">from the air<\\/a> and the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20834871976\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">meal was delicious<\\/a>.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>The next day I got on the humpback tour but had two hours until it started. Naturally, I went for a hike. Went back up the Mount Roberts Tramway and hiked at full speed towards Mount Roberts.  After an hour, I had made it up to a point where the trail was mostly slick rock interspersed with slippery mud and the wind\\/rain was blowing at me in an abusive manner. Even with full rain gear all zipped up, the water had found its way in along my face and neckline.  Turned around and showed up for the whale tour looking a bit damp.  The whale tour was another trip where it somehow exceeded expectations. Over an hour of humpback whales bubbled feeding, diving, and even a breach. There are videos but they really do not do the experience justice.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Thanks to a ferry breaking down, another ferry not running because of severe weather, and an overcrowded hostel I took a flight to Sitka the next morning. Numerous people had expounded on the beauty of Sitka and I felt it was worth a visit.  A raging storm had it Sitka that morning and dumped 2.5 inches of rain in six hours, triggering numerous landslides including one that took out a new hours with three people inside. When I arrived it was thankfully just a drizzle so I walked the mile into down and had a late breakfast at the Larkspur Cafe.  A very Portland vibe hit me at that cafe, made even more powerful by the Free box on the porch containing a VHS set of Star Trek movies.  On the way to the hostel I passed a community library built to resemble a TARDIS.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>The hostel did not open until 6pm, so I walked over to the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.alaskaraptor.org\\/\\\">Alaska Raptor Center<\\/a>, which provides medical treatment to injured birds and teach the public about Alaska\'s raptor population.  Another one of those gems of Alaska that is relatively cheap and well worth a visit.  The entrance had two owls <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20238735164\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">greeting visitors<\\/a> and then you tour through both indoor and outdoor enclosures full of bald eagles and other birds. All the birds have names and classrooms around the world can \\\"adopt\\\" a bird and receive materials and lessons about the raptors.  I wandered around for an hour absorbing and admiring it all.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>The next day I had planned on going for a hike up behind Sitka to the summit of Gavan Hill.  However, when I reached the trailhead (after going out of my way to fetch a bit of bear spray since I was hiking solo), I discovered the Sitka Fire Department had closed it because of landslide danger. Phooey!  Considering how much damage I had seen already on the well maintained Cross Trail, it was not too surprisingly that the higher, steeper slopes were dangerous in these conditions.  Meeting another hosteler, I instead headed up the Indian River trail with him.  The trail was in reasonably good conditions, if you did not mind dead salmon being littered about.  Seems the rains had so swollen the river that the salmon had been able to swim up onto the trail and beyond, and then gotten trapped when the waters receded.  Still, the forest was gorgeous and full of life.  The smell of a healthy, thriving forest is not to be beat.  And even miles up the trail, we saw salmon in the river still heading up to spawn.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>By the end of that hike though, I definitely needed to do a bit of laundry.  And I finally decided that my shoes had to go. They had been well used for trail running before the trip and the combination of rain, mud, salt water, and dead salmon had made them so unpleasantly ripe that even I was finding them too much.  An outfitter in town serendipitously had a nice pair of Brooks in my size for 40% off too.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>The next day Sitka brought out the pretty.  A bit of rain in the morning but then partly cloudy and sunny the rest of the day.  I grabbed my book and made the most of it by simply lounging around town.  My tendency to go full bore meant I had not taken a day off for the entire trip just to recover and enjoy the scenery.  Remedied that.  Saw quite a bit of wildlife too, including two <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.flickr.com\\/photos\\/133323973@N07\\/20868579641\\/in\\/album-72157657725794351\\/\\\">sea lions having dinner<\\/a> in the marina.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>That night I reviewed my credit card balance and decided that after an intense two week whirlwind through SE Alaska that it was time to head back south and start thinking about finding employment once more.  A truly amazing trip.\\r\\n<\\/p>\"}}', '2015-09-20 18:39:03', '2015-09-20 18:39:03', '9b17e216-de80-49a4-92c2-fc39aeac783d'),
