 ('459', '197', '1', '1', 'en_us', '1', NULL, '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"New Zealand War Against the Fruit Fly.\",\"slug\":\"new-zealand-war-against-the-fruit-fly\",\"postDate\":1450117943,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.bbc.com\\/news\\/blogs-news-from-elsewhere-35006888\\\">Link<\\/a>.  Announcement was quickly followed by a response from Fruit Fly High Command:\\n<\\/p><blockquote>Insects!  We can\'t be consumed by our petty differences anymore. We will be united in our common interests. Perhaps it\'s fate that today is the Fourth of July, and we will be fighting for our freedom... Not from tyranny, oppression, or persecution... but from annihilation. We are fighting for our right to live. To exist. And should we win the day, the Fourth of July will no longer be known as an American holiday, but as the day the Insects of the world declared in one voice: \\\"We will not go quietly into the night!\\\" We will not vanish without a fight! We\'re going to live on! We\'re going to survive! Today we celebrate our Insectpendence Day!<br>\\n\\t<\\/blockquote>\"}}', '2015-12-14 18:32:23', '2015-12-14 18:32:23', 'e084fd76-8aa4-4eb9-ad4b-1d4093d1df2e'),
 ('460', '198', '1', '1', 'en_us', '1', NULL, '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Why we\\u2019re going back to the Moon\\u2014with or without NASA\",\"slug\":\"why-were-going-back-to-the-moon-with-or-without-nasa\",\"postDate\":1450238171,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/arstechnica.com\\/science\\/2015\\/12\\/why-were-going-back-to-the-moon-with-or-without-nasa\\/\\\">Link<\\/a>. ArsTechnica dives deep into why the discovery of water on the moon means we might have a solid chance of transplanting a few humans on other worlds before I die.<\\/p>\"}}', '2015-12-16 03:56:11', '2015-12-16 03:56:11', 'c73cbd2e-45d8-4904-a314-b820dada80cc'),
 ('461', '199', '1', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Laravel, Craft CMS, Subdirectories, File Caching, and Gzip...Oh My!\",\"slug\":\"laravel-craft-cms-subdirectories-file-caching-and-gzip-oh-my\",\"postDate\":1450240210,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Last month, I launched the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/bookbran.ch\\\">new site<\\/a> for a client\'s online resource for books. While only a beta (client just announced it to friends this week), it is a taste of things to come as I am about halfway through the development for version 2.  When we launched, I put a note in my calendar to set up <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/HTTPS\\\">HTTPS<\\/a> once the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/letsencrypt.org\\\">Let\'s Encrypt<\\/a> certificate authority hit beta.  Free, open, and automated certificates for websites? No brainer, especially given how important it is that we as developers protect both our and our users\' data.<\\/p><p>Naturally, with any new tool, I played around with it on my own personal site before using it for a client. I also discovered a couple weeks back that nginx was configured on my server without any default caching settings for images and other media files.  No gzip compression either. Proverbial two (three?) birds with one stone time.<\\/p><p>I am using Homestead for my local development and the godsend that is <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/forge.laravel.com\\\">Laravel Forge<\\/a> for deployment on <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.digitalocean.com\\/?refcode=e4cc0aa98b32\\\">Digital Ocean<\\/a>.  After restarting the server to insure all packages were up to date, I used its built in tool for setting up Let\'s Encrypt and let it churn for a few moments while it installed the required pieces and created the certificates.<\\/p>\"}}', '2015-12-16 04:30:11', '2015-12-16 04:30:11', '9ea10a0c-2327-46f6-8a47-5f956f243655'),
 ('462', '199', '1', '1', 'en_us', '2', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Laravel, Craft CMS, Subdirectories, File Caching, and Gzip...Oh My!\",\"slug\":\"laravel-craft-cms-subdirectories-file-caching-and-gzip-oh-my\",\"postDate\":1450240200,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Last month, I launched the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/bookbran.ch\\\">new site<\\/a> for a client\'s online resource for books. While only a beta (client just announced it to friends this week), it is a taste of things to come as I am about halfway through the development for version 2.  When we launched, I put a note in my calendar to set up <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/HTTPS\\\">HTTPS<\\/a> once the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/letsencrypt.org\\\">Let\'s Encrypt<\\/a> certificate authority hit beta.  Free, open, and automated certificates for websites? No brainer, especially given how important it is that we as developers protect both our and our users\' data.<\\/p><p>Naturally, with any new tool, I played around with it on my own personal site before using it for a client. I also discovered a couple weeks back that nginx was configured on my server without any default caching settings for images and other media files.  No gzip compression either. Proverbial two (three?) birds with one stone time.<\\/p><p>I am using Homestead for my local development and the godsend that is <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/forge.laravel.com\\\">Laravel Forge<\\/a> for deployment on <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.digitalocean.com\\/?refcode=e4cc0aa98b32\\\">Digital Ocean<\\/a>.  After restarting the server to insure all packages were up to date, I used its built in tool for setting up Let\'s Encrypt and let it churn for a few moments while it installed the required pieces and created the certificates.<\\/p>\"}}', '2015-12-16 04:30:21', '2015-12-16 04:30:21', '982966b7-2be8-4c93-9c5a-1d1678467365'),
 ('463', '199', '1', '1', 'en_us', '3', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Laravel, Craft CMS, Subdirectories, File Caching, and Gzip...Oh My!\",\"slug\":\"laravel-craft-cms-subdirectories-file-caching-and-gzip-oh-my\",\"postDate\":1450240200,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Last month, I launched the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/bookbran.ch\\\">new site<\\/a> for a client\'s online resource for books. While only a beta (client just announced it to friends this week), it is a taste of things to come as I am about halfway through the development for version 2.  When we launched, I put a note in my calendar to set up <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/HTTPS\\\">HTTPS<\\/a> once the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/letsencrypt.org\\\">Let\'s Encrypt<\\/a> certificate authority hit beta.  Free, open, and automated certificates for websites? No brainer, especially given how important it is that we as developers protect both our and our users\' data.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Naturally, with any new tool, I played around with it on my own personal site before using it for a client. I also discovered a couple weeks back that nginx was configured on my server without any default caching settings for images and other media files.  No gzip compression either. Proverbial two (three?) birds with one stone time.\\r\\n<\\/p><blockquote>You can read along and then at the bottom I will provide links to my nginx.conf and an example site configuration file.\\r\\n<\\/blockquote><p>I am using Homestead for my local development and the godsend that is <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/forge.laravel.com\\\">Laravel Forge<\\/a> for deployment on <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.digitalocean.com\\/?refcode=e4cc0aa98b32\\\">Digital Ocean<\\/a>.  After restarting the server to insure all packages were up to date, I used its built in tool for setting up Let\'s Encrypt and let it churn for a few moments while it installed the required pieces and created the certificate.  Hit Activate and my site was magically running with HTTPS.  Golden.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Well. Almost.  I went to <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.ssllabs.com\\/ssltest\\/\\\">SSL Labs\' Analyzer<\\/a> and only got a B.  Seems the default Diffie-Hellman parameters on nginx are <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/Logjam_(computer_security)\\\">vulnerable<\\/a> to attack.  <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/sysops.forlaravel.com\\/diffie-hellman-fix\\\">The fix<\\/a> is relatively simple and if you are familiar with the command line and editing via vi, you should be done in no time.  However, I wanted to insure that all of my SSL configuration options in nginx were as up to date as possible based on recommended practices.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>One of the most important ones is which ciphers your server will use and in what order.  Mozilla has a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/wiki.mozilla.org\\/Security\\/Server_Side_TLS#Modern_compatibility\\\">fantastic page<\\/a> for explaining ciphers and what they recommend depending on your needs.  Not only that, they have a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/mozilla.github.io\\/server-side-tls\\/ssl-config-generator\\/\\\">SSL Configuration Generator<\\/a> where you specify your server, version, and profile and it spits out the SSL settings it recommends.  Very shiny.\\r\\n<\\/p><p><strong>Pro Tip: <\\/strong>You can find your nginx and openssl versions by running <code>nginx -v<\\/code> and <code>openssl version<\\/code>\\r\\n<\\/p><p><strong><\\/strong>If you\'re like me, you are probably running more than one site though under one or more domains. Most of these SSL configuration options do not need to duplicated for every site configuration file, obviously, and can be all put in the <em>nginx.conf<\\/em> file. Which brings us to the gzip and caching portion of our entry.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Matt Stauffer wrote a solid article on <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/mattstauffer.co\\/blog\\/enabling-gzip-on-nginx-servers-including-laravel-forge\\\">how to enable gzip for your nginx server<\\/a> by adding a couple dozen lines to <em>nginx.conf<\\/em>. I followed it exactly.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>As for <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/serversforhackers.com\\/nginx-caching\\/\\\">caching headers<\\/a>, this is where it got a bit tricky for me.  First, it has to go in your site configuration as you likely only want to cache specific file types and some file types might have slightly different cache times.  Second, if you are running two different applications\\u2013let us say Laravel for the site and <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/craftcms.com\\\">Craft CMS<\\/a> for a blog\\u2013the configuration gets a little tricky as you already have two different <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/nginx.org\\/en\\/docs\\/http\\/ngx_http_core_module.html#location\\\">location<\\/a> blocks.  You cannot simply set up a third location for media files as nginx will only match one.  You can get around this by having additional, more specific grep matching for your location blocks or simply add conditionals. I went with the latter.  This is a short example of what I have in my site configuration for my Laravel and Craft CMS combo site:\\r\\n<\\/p><pre>location \\/ {\\r\\n    try_files $uri $uri\\/ \\/index.php?$query_string;\\r\\n    if ($uri ~* \\\"\\\\.(?:jpg|jpeg|gif|png|ico|cur|gz|svg|svgz|mp4|ogg|ogv)\\\" ) {\\r\\n        expires 1M;\\r\\n        access_log off;\\r\\n        add_header Cache-Control \\\"public\\\";\\r\\n    }\\r\\n    if ($uri ~* \\\"\\\\.(?:css|js)\\\" ) {\\r\\n        expires 1y;\\r\\n        access_log off;\\r\\n        add_header Cache-Control \\\"public\\\";\\r\\n    }\\r\\n}\\r\\nlocation \\/blog {\\r\\n    try_files $uri $uri\\/ \\/blog\\/index.php?p=$query_string;\\r\\n}\\r\\n<\\/pre><p>Pretty simple and it works. Honestly, that is pretty much all that I hope for with servers at this point. <\\/p><p>It probably is worth emphasizing that I do not consider myself a DevOps expert and while this works for me, I am in no way putting this solution up on high as The Solution (TM, patent pending).<\\/p><p><br><\\/p>\"}}', '2015-12-16 05:14:17', '2015-12-16 05:14:17', 'f795ee5a-8e7b-4856-9db0-963b2837f407'),
 ('464', '199', '1', '1', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Laravel, Craft CMS, Subdirectories, File Caching, and Gzip...Oh My!\",\"slug\":\"laravel-craft-cms-subdirectories-file-caching-and-gzip-oh-my\",\"postDate\":1450240200,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Last month, I launched the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/bookbran.ch\\\">new site<\\/a> for a client\'s online resource for books. While only a beta (client just announced it to friends this week), it is a taste of things to come as I am about halfway through the development for version 2.  When we launched, I put a note in my calendar to set up <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/HTTPS\\\">HTTPS<\\/a> once the <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/letsencrypt.org\\\">Let\'s Encrypt<\\/a> certificate authority hit beta.  Free, open, and automated certificates for websites? No brainer, especially given how important it is that we as developers protect both our and our users\' data.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Naturally, with any new tool, I played around with it on my own personal site before using it for a client. I also discovered a couple weeks back that nginx was configured on my server without any default caching settings for images and other media files.  No gzip compression either. Proverbial two (three?) birds with one stone time.\\r\\n<\\/p><blockquote>You can read along and then at the bottom I will provide links to my nginx.conf and an example site configuration file.\\r\\n<\\/blockquote><p>I am using Homestead for my local development and the godsend that is <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/forge.laravel.com\\\">Laravel Forge<\\/a> for deployment on <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.digitalocean.com\\/?refcode=e4cc0aa98b32\\\">Digital Ocean<\\/a>.  After restarting the server to insure all packages were up to date, I used its built in tool for setting up Let\'s Encrypt and let it churn for a few moments while it installed the required pieces and created the certificate.  Hit Activate and my site was magically running with HTTPS.  Golden.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Well. Almost.  I went to <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.ssllabs.com\\/ssltest\\/\\\">SSL Labs\' Analyzer<\\/a> and only got a B.  Seems the default Diffie-Hellman parameters on nginx are <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/Logjam_(computer_security)\\\">vulnerable<\\/a> to attack.  <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/sysops.forlaravel.com\\/diffie-hellman-fix\\\">The fix<\\/a> is relatively simple and if you are familiar with the command line and editing via vi, you should be done in no time.  However, I wanted to insure that all of my SSL configuration options in nginx were as up to date as possible based on recommended practices.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>One of the most important ones is which ciphers your server will use and in what order.  Mozilla has a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/wiki.mozilla.org\\/Security\\/Server_Side_TLS#Modern_compatibility\\\">fantastic page<\\/a> for explaining ciphers and what they recommend depending on your needs.  Not only that, they have a <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/mozilla.github.io\\/server-side-tls\\/ssl-config-generator\\/\\\">SSL Configuration Generator<\\/a> where you specify your server, version, and profile and it spits out the SSL settings it recommends.  Very shiny.\\r\\n<\\/p><p><strong>Pro Tip: <\\/strong>You can find your nginx and openssl versions by running <code>nginx -v<\\/code> and <code>openssl version<\\/code>\\r\\n<\\/p><p><strong><\\/strong>If you\'re like me, you are probably running more than one site though under one or more domains. Most of these SSL configuration options do not need to duplicated for every site configuration file, obviously, and can be all put in the <em>nginx.conf<\\/em> file. Which brings us to the gzip and caching portion of our entry.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Matt Stauffer wrote a solid article on <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/mattstauffer.co\\/blog\\/enabling-gzip-on-nginx-servers-including-laravel-forge\\\">how to enable gzip for your nginx server<\\/a> by adding a couple dozen lines to <em>nginx.conf<\\/em>. I followed it exactly.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>As for <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/serversforhackers.com\\/nginx-caching\\/\\\">caching headers<\\/a>, this is where it got a bit tricky for me.  First, it has to go in your site configuration as you likely only want to cache specific file types and some file types might have slightly different cache times.  Second, if you are running two different applications\\u2013let us say Laravel for the site and <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/craftcms.com\\\">Craft CMS<\\/a> for a blog\\u2013the configuration gets a little tricky as you already have two different <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/nginx.org\\/en\\/docs\\/http\\/ngx_http_core_module.html#location\\\">location<\\/a> blocks.  You cannot simply set up a third location for media files as nginx will only match one.  You can get around this by having additional, more specific grep matching for your location blocks or simply add conditionals. I went with the latter.  This is a short example of what I have in my site configuration for my Laravel and Craft CMS combo site:\\r\\n<\\/p><pre>location \\/ {\\r\\n    try_files $uri $uri\\/ \\/index.php?$query_string;\\r\\n    if ($uri ~* \\\"\\\\.(?:jpg|jpeg|gif|png|ico|cur|gz|svg|svgz|mp4|ogg|ogv)\\\" ) {\\r\\n        expires 1M;\\r\\n        access_log off;\\r\\n        add_header Cache-Control \\\"public\\\";\\r\\n    }\\r\\n    if ($uri ~* \\\"\\\\.(?:css|js)\\\" ) {\\r\\n        expires 1y;\\r\\n        access_log off;\\r\\n        add_header Cache-Control \\\"public\\\";\\r\\n    }\\r\\n}\\r\\nlocation \\/blog {\\r\\n    try_files $uri $uri\\/ \\/blog\\/index.php?p=$query_string;\\r\\n}\\r\\n<\\/pre><p>Pretty simple and it works. Honestly, that is pretty much all that I hope for with servers at this point. <\\/p><p>It probably is worth emphasizing that I do not consider myself a DevOps expert and while this works for me, I am in no way putting this solution up on high as The Solution (TM,