 ('499', '220', '1', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Sanders Coverage by NY Times\",\"slug\":\"sanders-coverage-by-ny-times\",\"postDate\":1458753480,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>It is a bit mind-blowing how skewed the coverage for Sanders has been compared to Clinton on the NY Times. Even when he wins multiple states like he did yesterday, they often put him in as an afterthought or <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.nytimes.com\\/2016\\/03\\/23\\/us\\/politics\\/election-results.html?ref=politics\\\">present him negatively<\\/a>.  And then they post additional articles with titles like \\\"<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.nytimes.com\\/interactive\\/2016\\/03\\/16\\/upshot\\/clinton-sanders-democratic-delegate-lead.html?ref=politics\\\">Clinton\\u2019s Growing Delegate Lead Is Nearly Unbeatable<\\/a>\\\" just underneath.  Finally, the Times editors have been caught making <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/publiceditor.blogs.nytimes.com\\/2016\\/03\\/17\\/new-york-times-bernie-sanders-coverage-public-editor\\/\\\">substantive changes to already published articles<\\/a> on Sanders to change the tone and perspective.  <\\/p><p>I hope they realize that only <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.nytimes.com\\/interactive\\/2016\\/us\\/elections\\/primary-calendar-and-results.html\\\">half of the states have voted<\\/a> so far in the primaries and this race for the Democratic nomination is FAR from over.  If anything, the media\'s coverage of Sanders makes me support him that much more while liking Clinton and her ties to big money that much less.<br><\\/p>\"}}', '2016-03-23 17:18:00', '2016-03-23 17:18:00', '11652dbc-4ee4-4e0d-8f86-c980962023ed'),
 ('500', '221', '1', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Fuck Yes or No\",\"slug\":\"fuck-yes-or-no\",\"postDate\":1458757020,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>I remember reading this \\\"<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/markmanson.net\\/fuck-yes\\\">Fuck Yes or No<\\/a>\\\" for dating a couple years ago and generally agreeing with the approach.  Not just for dating but pretty much all serious relationships in one\'s life.  Love and work, being the big ones, naturally. It does seem incredibly odd that people would spent hours of their day, months of their year, and years of their life on relationships or jobs that are merely OK.<\\/p><p>I mention this only because I am Once Again (TM, patent pending) trying to decide what to do with my life. It waxes and wanes, as you can imagine.  For five months here I have had steady work as a Lead Developer for two startups on a contract basis. Caught up on all the PHP\\/<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/laravel.com\\\">Laravel<\\/a> skills and have become a fair hand at using <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/vuejs.org\\\">Vue.js<\\/a> for building interactive pages and single page applications.  Figured out how to use <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/github.com\\/laravel\\/homestead\\\">Homestead<\\/a> locally and even more experience with <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/forge.laravel.com\\\">Forge<\\/a> for provisioning and deploying too. Learning is good. My Full Stack Developer skills remain strong.<\\/p><p>All the while I have been hunting for that next opportunity.  The job that will make me want to become invested in a company and stay around for a couple years.  People like me thrive on intensive projects that we believe in.  My Reed degree, EllisLab, Pre-Medicine, the Pacific Crest Trail.  I remember these times as the most positive and transformative because I was completely invested in the experience of working towards those goals.<\\/p><p>For a short time I thought ImpactFlow might become that but it rather quickly soured and became obvious that it was not going to reach its potential.  When I felt it sliding into the realm of <\\/p>\"}}', '2016-03-23 18:17:00', '2016-03-23 18:17:00', 'f1a6e324-d5d7-474f-be71-dd65e8489aa0'),
