tting issues.  Not a huge fan of Google Drive but if I am going to share this data with others, I may have to switch to using it for the daily updates too.  Bugger.\\r\\n<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><iframe id=\\\"pageswitcher-content\\\" frameborder=\\\"0\\\" marginheight=\\\"0\\\" marginwidth=\\\"0\\\" src=\\\"https:\\/\\/docs.google.com\\/spreadsheets\\/d\\/1ss-h-AqmCKR57EpAr66E6jVs_9YyvwE4_M_LebdLf_8\\/pubhtml?gid=509608816&single=false&widget=true&headers=false\\\" style=\\\"display: block; width: 100%; height: 500px;\\\">\\r\\n<\\/iframe><p><br><\\/p><p>After I made the Compiled sheet with all the totals in one table, I noticed a pretty substantial data oversight.  While I am keeping track of time for activities like running, biking and weights, I am completely skipping it for things like swimming, snowshoeing, and alpine touring. Swimming is reasonably calculable thanks to me being pretty consistent at a 30 minute mile at the moment. Alpine touring and snowshoeing, though, would have to be educated guesses based on my remembrance of the day and any photos I took during the activity. Back of the napkin workings have me missing about 35 hours worth of time.<\\/p><p>So, after 14 weeks, what do I see here?<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-04-10 03:15:54', '2016-04-10 03:15:54', '7354fc73-58ed-4209-af65-ae34d5c8b8eb'),
 ('518', '223', '1', '1', 'en_us', '13', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"2016 Activity Log \\u2013 An Attempt at Structure\",\"slug\":\"2016-activity-log\",\"postDate\":1460244360,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>As an active, outdoorsy, geeky, and nerdy individual who gobbles up medical studies and gear reviews nearly every single day, I have oddly never made a real record of my athletic activities. Off and on I have dabbled with the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.mapmyfitness.com\\\">MapMyFitness<\\/a> sites to help figure out how far I ran or what the elevation profile was for a bike ride, but not with any true serious intention to keep it up to date or analyze the data later. In my own way I was being a purist to my belief that the activity itself is the worthier part than any sort of personal record or achievement. My little stab at applying Kantian moral philosophy to athletics.  Gods, I just typed that out and rolled my <em>own<\\/em> eyes at it.  ::slow applause::\\r\\n<\\/p><p>For reasons I cannot really fathom, part of me issued a proclamation stating that 2016 Shall be the Year That Activities Shall be Tracked.  I sat down at the end of December and created a spreadsheet for January with a row for every single day and columns for my common outdoorsy or athletic activities.  And, I started keeping a record of most everything I did in that spreadsheet. I also downloaded the Strava app onto my phone to help track my runs and bike rides. Been far less diligent with Strava as I am often not willing to carry it with me on shorter runs or rides.  Cases where having a watch with GPS capabilities might be nice.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>A copy of the current spreadsheet data is below, thanks to Google Drive.  I have a Numbers document that I have been using locally the past few months but the iCloud sharing ability is godawful slow when rendering the spreadsheet, so I just pulled my Numbers document into Google and fixed a dozen formatting issues.  Not a huge fan of Google Drive but if I am going to share this data with others, I may have to switch to using it for the daily updates too.  Bugger.\\r\\n<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><iframe id=\\\"pageswitcher-content\\\" frameborder=\\\"0\\\" marginheight=\\\"0\\\" marginwidth=\\\"0\\\" src=\\\"https:\\/\\/docs.google.com\\/spreadsheets\\/d\\/1ss-h-AqmCKR57EpAr66E6jVs_9YyvwE4_M_LebdLf_8\\/pubhtml?gid=509608816&single=false&widget=true&headers=false\\\" style=\\\"display: block; width: 100%; height: 500px;\\\">\\r\\n<\\/iframe><p><br><\\/p><p>After I made the Compiled sheet with all the totals in one table, I noticed a pretty substantial data oversight.  While I am keeping track of time for activities like running, biking and weights, I am completely skipping it for things like swimming, snowshoeing, and alpine touring. Swimming is reasonably calculable thanks to me being pretty consistent at a 30 minute mile at the moment. Alpine touring and snowshoeing, though, would have to be educated guesses based on my remembrance of the day and any photos I took during the activity. Back of the napkin workings have me missing about 35 hours worth of time.<\\/p><p>So, after 14 weeks, what do I see here? I am averaging about 9.3 hours of exercise per week.  That is with me taking usually two rest days per week (and an entire week off at the beginning of March).  On days I exercise, I am averaging about two hours of activity. Not too bad.<\\/p><p>Comparing February and March, it is quite apparent that I slashed my running in order to start swimming and also go biking, hiking, and alpine touring.  What is not apparent is that the runs I did in March were done quite a bit faster, resulting in me pulling of an 8:30\\/mile pace during a trail run today, which is a minute faster than my average time in February.<\\/p><p>One rather embarrassing statistic is my time spent stretching. 460 minutes in January, 295 minutes in February, but only 85 minutes in March. <\\/p>\"}}', '2016-04-10 03:24:04', '2016-04-10 03:24:04', 'c8c45776-562b-4c74-b68d-653f3399f301'),
