 ('543', '225', '1', '1', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"1\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Strava Wars - The Search for More Data\",\"slug\":\"strava-wars-the-search-for-more-data\",\"postDate\":null,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>A year ago, when I switched from training for a 50K trail run to training to bike 100+ miles for <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.reachthebeach.org\\/\\\">Reach the Beach<\\/a>, I finally downloaded the Strava app for my iPhone.  At the periphery of my knowledge, I knew the app existed and that multiple professional athletes used it to publicly share their training, but\\u2013just like my <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/reedmaniac.com\\/blog\\/entries\\/2016-activity-log\\\">training log<\\/a>\\u2013for a long time it seemed a bit more serious than I was willing to be.<\\/p><p>Curiosity got the better of me though and I became quite curious to see how fast I was flying down some of those hills in the West Hills or in the Columbia Gorge. And yes, a bit of bragging rights too. My profile is located <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.strava.com\\/athletes\\/3769422\\\">here<\\/a>.  As you can see my usage is a bit sporadic. Entire months and multiple weeks have no data, despite them being in the middle of prime  running or biking season.  What can I say, I am inconsistent.  Also, I have an amazing tendency to forget to turn the start the Strava app (and am not yet cool enough to have a GPS-capable watch). While I love my phone, I have a tendency to ignore it as a computer device as it seems silly to be so consistently connected to the web when you are Outside\\u2122.<\\/p><p>As far as the data Strava provides post-run or post-ride, it is quite a bit of fun to see what my average speed is, the elevation gained, and what my mile times are for various sections of my run or ride.  Just recently, during a downhill section on Newberry Rd., I apparently hit a maximum speed of <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.strava.com\\/activities\\/538796948\\\